== A Day in the Life: Credit Analyst

=== 7:30 AM – Pre-Market Preparation
Arrive early to review overnight developments:
- Check Bloomberg for Asian and European credit market moves
- Scan ASX announcements for portfolio holdings
- Review emails from issuers, brokers, and internal trading desk
- Identify any urgent issues requiring immediate attention (e.g., unexpected earnings miss, downgrade announcement)

=== 8:00 AM – Morning Investment Team Meeting
Join the daily team standup covering:
- Global market overview and credit spread movements
- New issuance calendar for the day (e.g., "Vicinity Centres looking to print \$300m 5-year senior notes")
- Portfolio positions requiring discussion
- Upcoming company results or material events
Today's agenda: Portfolio Manager flags that Qantas is reporting earnings next week and wants a refresh on the credit view given recent fuel cost pressures.

=== 8:30 AM – New Issue Analysis: Vicinity Centres Bond
Receive offering circular for new Vicinity Centres bond. Quick turnaround needed—management wants decision by 2pm:
- Read executive summary and key terms
- Pull latest financials from Bloomberg and previous analyst model
- Update model with latest occupancy rates, development pipeline, refinancing schedule
- Compare pricing (indicative spread: +140bps over swap) to secondary market comparable (Scentre Group trading at +125bps)
- Review property portfolio quality and tenant diversification
- Check covenant package—negative pledge, change of control provisions
- Draft brief recommendation memo highlighting: adequate coverage metrics, but exposure to retail downturn; spread looks fair but not compelling

=== 10:30 AM – Company Management Call: Coca-Cola Amatil
Join Portfolio Manager on quarterly update call with CCL treasury:
- Listen to management commentary on volume growth, margin pressures from input costs
- Ask clarifying questions about upcoming debt maturity refinancing strategy
- Note management's confidence in maintaining BBB rating despite headwinds
- After call, update internal credit file with key takeaways

=== 11:30 AM – Deep Work: Qantas Credit Review
Focus on comprehensive credit analysis ahead of earnings:
- Build updated financial model incorporating latest fuel price assumptions, capacity growth, cost-out initiatives
- Calculate projected leverage metrics (Net Debt/EBITDA expected to improve to 1.8x from 2.1x)
- Review fleet commitments and capital expenditure obligations
- Assess refinancing risk—significant maturity in 18 months
- Compare to pre-COVID credit profile and international airline peers
- Consider tail risks: new COVID variant, carbon regulations, further industrial action
- Draft 3-page credit memo with updated recommendation (maintain Overweight position)

=== 1:00 PM – Quick Lunch at Desk
Eat while monitoring Bloomberg for breaking news and responding to trader query about pricing on Medibank bond

=== 1:30 PM – Credit Committee Meeting
Present Vicinity Centres new issue recommendation to investment committee:
- Walk through credit strengths and weaknesses
- Defend pricing view against PM who thinks spread is too tight
- Discuss portfolio fit and size of allocation if participating
- Committee decides to take \$5m allocation at +145bps if achievable
- Note action items: submit order to trading desk, update portfolio allocation models

=== 2:30 PM – Research and Writing: Sector Update on Healthcare REITs
Continue work on broader sector piece examining healthcare property REITs:
- Analyse demographic trends supporting aged care facilities
- Review regulatory changes to aged care funding
- Compare operators: Healthco, Vital Healthcare (NZ-listed but significant Aus exposure)
- Update sector framework document maintained for the team
- This longer-term project helps build sector expertise

=== 3:30 PM – Ad-hoc Request: Westpac Tier 2 Trading Update
Trading desk notices Westpac Tier 2 bonds widening 15bps today:
- Quick check for news—nothing obvious
- Review broader bank T2 market—others stable
- Likely technical driven by fund liquidation (traders hearing market colour)
- Email PM: no fundamental concern, potential opportunity if weakness continues

=== 4:30 PM – Portfolio Monitoring and Watchlist Review
Systematic review of watchlist positions:
- Check bonds trading wider than 20bps move threshold
- Review upcoming earnings calendar for next week
- Update credit watch spreadsheet with status notes
- Flag to PM: Aurizon reporting Wednesday, may want to schedule discussion Friday

=== 5:15 PM – End of Day Wrap-up
- Respond to outstanding emails
- Update task list for tomorrow: finish Qantas memo, follow up on Vicinity allocation, prepare for Dexus roadshow tomorrow afternoon
- Check primary market calendar for tomorrow
- Quick scan of after-hours ASX announcements

=== 6:00 PM – Depart
Most days finish around 6pm, though can run later during busy periods (earnings season, volatile markets, heavy new issuance pipeline)

=== Evening (Optional)
- Some analysts use evening for CFA study or reading industry research
- During busy periods, may work from home on longer-term research projects
- Check phone occasionally if awaiting urgent developments

