== Career Progression Pathways

=== Entry Point: Credit Analyst
*Typical Background*
- Bachelor's degree in Finance, Commerce, Economics, or Accounting
- Some analysts enter from Big Four audit or corporate finance roles
- Strong academic record (Distinction average or higher typically expected)
- Internship experience in investment management, investment banking, or commercial banking valued

*Initial Responsibilities*
- Supporting senior analysts with data gathering and model updates
- Covering smaller issuers or lower-priority sectors
- Conducting initial screening of new issues
- Building foundational credit analysis skills

=== Year 2-3: Mid-Level Credit Analyst
*Progression Markers*
- Taking ownership of 2-3 sectors with limited supervision
- Presenting directly to Portfolio Managers and investment committee
- Developing relationships with company management teams
- Building reputation for quality, timely analysis

*Expanding Responsibilities*
- Leading coverage of key issuers within assigned sectors
- Mentoring new analysts joining the team
- Participating in due diligence for new fund strategies
- Contributing to thought leadership (e.g., sector white papers)

=== Year 4-6: Senior Credit Analyst
*Role Evolution*
- Full ownership of high-priority sectors (e.g., financials, infrastructure)
- Regular interaction with C-suite executives and corporate treasury
- Representing the fund at industry conferences
- Input into portfolio strategy and positioning

*Skills Development*
- Deep sector expertise recognised internally and externally
- Strong track record of credit recommendations (avoiding defaults, identifying opportunities)
- Leadership within analyst team

=== Year 6-10: Portfolio Manager / Head of Credit
*Two Primary Pathways*

*1. Portfolio Manager – Investment Grade / High Yield*
- Direct portfolio management responsibility
- P&L accountability for fund performance
- Client-facing role in presenting strategy and results
- Risk management and portfolio construction
- Team leadership and analyst mentoring

*2. Head of Credit / Senior Investment Strategist*
- Oversight of entire credit analyst team
- Setting research priorities and coverage framework
- Contributing to firm-wide investment process
- Thought leadership and external representation
- May retain some portfolio management responsibilities

=== Alternative Career Pivots

*Lateral Moves within Fund Management*
- *Investment Banking* (Credit teams at institutional banks): Leveraging credit skills for syndicated lending, leveraged finance, or restructuring
- *Private Credit*: Direct lending funds increasingly popular; credit analysis skills highly transferable
- *Equity Analysis*: Some credit analysts transition to equity research, bringing differentiated perspective on balance sheet risk
- *Risk Management*: Credit risk roles at banks, super funds, or regulators

*Buy-Side Moves*
- *Superannuation Funds*: In-house credit teams at large funds (AustralianSuper, UniSuper, Aware Super)
- *Insurance Companies*: Fixed income investing for asset-liability matching
- *Private Equity*: Leveraged buyout analysis overlaps significantly with high-yield credit analysis

*Other Financial Services*
- *Rating Agencies* (S&P, Moody's, Fitch): Leveraging credit expertise; becoming a published rating analyst
- *Sell-Side Research*: Credit research at institutional banks or independent brokers
- *Consulting*: Financial due diligence, restructuring advisory, regulatory consulting
- *Corporate Roles*: Investor relations, corporate treasury, M&A

