== What Makes a Successful Credit Analyst?

=== Intellectual Curiosity
The best analysts are naturally inquisitive:
- Constantly asking "what could go wrong?" when reviewing credits
- Reading broadly across business news, not just assigned sectors
- Challenging consensus views with independent research

=== Attention to Detail
Credit investing requires rigorous attention to detail:
- Catching footnote disclosures that signal emerging risks
- Identifying subtle changes in covenant language
- Spotting inconsistencies between management commentary and financial reality

=== Scepticism and Judgement
- Healthy scepticism toward management spin and optimistic projections
- Balancing quantitative metrics with qualitative judgement
- Knowing when to dig deeper versus accepting surface-level comfort

=== Resilience Under Pressure
- Managing tight deadlines during busy new issue periods
- Handling stress of wrong-way credit calls
- Continuing rigorous analysis during market volatility

=== Communication Skills
- Translating complex analysis into clear, actionable recommendations
- Defending credit views when challenged by senior stakeholders
- Building consensus in team debates

